description: This library provides a single client implementation to be used by AAI micro services for communicating via its REST API.
contribution_justification: The process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
contribution_requirements_justification:
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies describes requirements for acceptable contributions and is linked from the AAI project page. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style shows java code style.
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developer+Best+Practices
license_location_justification: Licence can be found in: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=aai/rest-client.git;a=blob;f=License.txt;h=c97ccb2ef72c2f18a5299fa8e8c380e01fcc109a;hb=HEAD

floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
repo_public_justification: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/aai/rest-client
repo_track_justification:
Tracking is provided by using a combination of JIRA and git history. Every commit has an user and a Jira number attached to it.

Git history for AAI Rest client's master branch:
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=aai/rest-client.git;a=shortlog;h=refs/heads/master

Jira for ONAP: https://jira.onap.org/secure/Dashboard.jspa
repo_interim_justification: Gerrit provides an temperate branch for reviewing and providing comments. Once approved, the code will be merged and the temperate branch will be removed
version_unique_justification: Release version is with format ${major}.${minor}.${patch} and will be updated accordingly for each release.
release_notes_justification: Release note can be found in http://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aai/aai-common.git/docs/release-notes.html
report_tracker_justification: Jira is used to track issues. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA
report_process_justification: The description of the process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA
report_archive_justification: The report of issues are listed here: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Issue+Reports
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Process on how to report a vulnerability can be found in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/ONAP+Vulnerability+Management
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Private vulnerability reports are not supported.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: There's no vulnerabilities reported so far.
build_justification: Jenkins is used to build the artifact. https://jenkins.onap.org/view/aai-rest-client/job/aai-rest-client-master-release-version-java-daily/
build_common_tools_justification: Maven are used to build the project
test_justification: The project uses junit to run the unit tests.
test_invocation_justification: Tests can be run, by running the command "mvn clean install"
tests_documented_added_justification: This is documented on our wiki: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Code+Coverage+and+Static+Code+Analysis
warnings_fixed_justification: The application logs the relevant warnings.
warnings_strict_justification: Build systems run the compile with test flag enabled by default. So any failure in test cases will fail the ci and the merge request.
static_analysis_often_justification: This is part of Continuous Integration on a daily basis
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: For each pull request, the project needs to be built successfully before the Merge option becomes activated. The test will be run automatically during the building process as well. Once build successfully and all tests has past, the Merge option will be activated.
hardening_justification: The project tries to use hardening mechanism whenever possible. Eg we use transaction id for tracking transactions through multiple services and also we use http headers to identify the application where possible
crypto_used_network_justification: The projects supports secure TLS and HTTPS and Insecure protocols are disabled by default in these applications, they cab be over-ridden by user configuration
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: All packages are delivered either as an jar artifact or a docker image. Incase of maven artifacts, they can be removed using the pom file. In case of docker container. We can delete the container we dont want. Also control the orchestration in Kubernetes if you want to exclude certain docker images.
dco_justification:
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies describes requirements for acceptable contributions and is linked from the AAI project page. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style
shows java code style. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developer+Best+Practices
governance_justification:
ONAP requires both a Developer Certificate of Origin (DCO), and a Contributor License Agreement (CLA).

https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Contribution+Agreements
code_of_conduct_justification: ONAP adheres to the Linux Foundation Code of Conduct, found at https://lfprojects.org/policies/code-of-conduct/
roles_responsibilities_justification:
The key roles in the project and their responsibilities are described at

https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Community+Offices+and+Governance

Current members are listed at

https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=8226539
access_continuity_justification: For AAI-Rest client we have 4 committers and multiple contributes who are listed in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Resources+and+Repositories#ResourcesandRepositories-ActiveandAvailableInventory All 4 committers have access and rights to maintain the code base, approve and review incoming changes and release a new version of the artifact. This will let the project continue with minimal to no interruption if one person is incapacitated. Also this project is controlled by the linux foundation so we can add more committers if needed
bus_factor_justification: The project covered in this report have more than 2 persons who actively contribute and maintain code. The following link provides with list of commit owners for the project https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/q/project:aai/rest-client+branch:master
documentation_roadmap_justification: Road map for AAI can be found in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/AAI+R3+Platform+Maturity?preview=%2F35523310%2F35523289%2FAAI+Roadmap+2018-01-05.pdf
documentation_architecture_justification: Architecture of AAI can be found in https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=1015836
documentation_quick_start_justification: Information on setting up ONAP can be found at https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/onap-developer/settingup/index.html
documentation_current_justification: Documentation is updated on a regular basis when needed.
internationalization_justification: It is not applicable at this point in time as the software will only be used by technical people and not by general public
sites_password_security_justification: The library does not store any password
maintenance_or_update_justification: This is a library API rather than a microservice, therefore upgrading would mean up versioning maven POM dependency.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: Vulnerabilities can be reported using the link https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=6591711 Currently we dont have any vulnerabilities reported, but the wiki page explains on how to report a vulnerability and how to report anonymously if you do not want the credit for it.
coding_standards_justification: Google coding style is used in ONAP https://github.com/google/styleguide
build_standard_variables_justification: The application does not create native binaries. (Some of the libraries it depends on do, but those are external.)
build_preserve_debug_justification: The application does not create native binaries. (Some of the libraries it depends on do, but those are external.)
build_non_recursive_justification: The application does not create native binaries. (Some of the libraries it depends on do, but those are external.)
build_repeatable_justification: All releases are tagged in gerrit(git), and the builds are controlled using jenkins. By providing the git tag information the same image can be build over and over again with same bit-for-bit result.
installation_standard_variables_justific: The library is packaged as a jar, and referenced as a maven dependency defined in the main application's pom file
installation_development_quick_justifica: All the components require only java and maven to begin with for a developer to quickly install and test it. Even for deployment using OOM and the right amount of resources, we can deploy the full AAI/ONAP suite in less than a day. The steps are documented in https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/oom.git/docs/oom_quickstart_guide.html
external_dependencies_justification: External dependencies are controlled using the pom file, which can be found in the root folder for the projects
dependency_monitoring_justification: NexusIQ sonar scan is run on all the projects on a weekly basis
updateable_reused_components_justificati: External components are maintained through Maven. The user can get a list of all included components using the maven dependency tree and can update or reuse as they see fit
interfaces_current_justification: We avoid depending on deprecated/obsolete functions.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: The library contains JUnit tests and executed during each maven build
regression_tests_added50_justification: When regressions occur, we add tests for them.
test_policy_mandated_justification: Contributing guide lines for development is recorded in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
implement_secure_design_justification: The project strives to implement secure design principles.
input_validation_justification: The project strives to validate all input to functions
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: Certificates are managed through AAF micro-service which will be deployed with ONAP suite
assurance_case_justification: Will work on for next release

name: JGit
description:
JGit is an EDL (new-style BSD) licensed, lightweight, pure Java library implementing the Git version control system:
- repository access routines
- network protocols
- core version control algorithms

also published on Maven central, latest release is here

repo_track_justification: we use git
repo_interim_justification: the repository contains all versions which are in code review or passed code review, also code review comment is retained forever in Gerrit Code Review
repo_distributed_justification: we use git and Gerrit Code Review
version_unique_justification: We follow semantic versioning and use 4 digit OSGi conform version numbers
version_tags_justification: we tag all releases with git tags
release_notes_justification:
release notes are published in the Eclipse project portal for each release
https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/technology.jgit
and the wiki
https://wiki.eclipse.org/JGit/New_and_Noteworthy
release_notes_vulns_justification: mentioned in release notes, security patches are sychronised with native git if necessary
report_process_justification:
that's described in the joint JGit / EGit contributor guide
https://wiki.eclipse.org/EGit/Contributor_Guide#Bugs
report_archive_justification:
mailing list and bug tracker are retained and can be searched
see https://www.eclipse.org/jgit/support/
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: no vulnerabilities reported in last 6 months
build_justification:
JGit can be built using Maven or Bazel, this is described in the contributor guide
https://wiki.eclipse.org/EGit/Contributor_Guide#Builds
build_common_tools_justification: Maven, Bazel are mature, established, common build tools
test_justification: JGIt has around 4500 unit tests which are part of the JGit source code repository
test_invocation_justification:
Maven build: run $ mvn test
Bazel build: run $ bazel test //...
tests_are_added_justification: this is checked during mandatory code review
warnings_justification: we run static checks during maven build currently using PMD, Spotbugs and Eclipse Java Compiler null analysis, using maven profile "javac" you can also run errorprone for additional checks
warnings_fixed_justification: We reject introduction of new warnings during mandatory code review. In case this was missed in a change review we follow up and fix such warnings.
warnings_strict_justification: at the moment JGit has around 210k LoC and only 15 warnings
crypto_password_storage_justification: JGit is a library, server applications using JGit may need to store password hashes, e.g. Gerrit Code Review does that
delivery_mitm_justification:
All centrally built (on Eclipse build infrastructure) build artefacts and delivery packages are signed with Eclipse certificates
Eclipse installer checks signatures
Build artefacts are delivered via Maven repositories (Eclipse nexus and Maven central)
delivery_unsigned_justification:
both Eclipse Nexus and Maven central provide SHA1 hash over https:
https://repo.eclipse.org/content/groups/jgit/org/eclipse/jgit/
https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/eclipse/jgit/
static_analysis_justification: PMD, SpotBugs (successor of FindBugs), Eclipse null analysis,
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
We do strict code review of all changes and require build and all tests to succeed for accepting any change in code review.
As soon as a change passed code review and reached the respective git branch we run a CI build job which runs build and all tests once more.
discussion_justification: see https://www.eclipse.org/jgit/support/ for mailing list, bug tracker and user forum
english_justification: all documentation and project communication is done in English

static_analysis_often_justification: This is part of Continuous Integration on a daily basis.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: We disallow SHA-1 or other insecure cryptographic algorithms.

discussion_justification: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Joining+the+ONAP+Technical+Community
crypto_used_network_justification: We use ssh2 internal to the cluster and TLS1.2+ for the external interfaces.
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: We support TLS certification verification before exchange of private information.

dco_justification: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies describes requirements for acceptable contributions and is linked from the AAI project page. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style shows java code style. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developer+Best+Practices
governance_justification:
ONAP requires both a Developer Certificate of Origin (DCO), and a Contributor License Agreement (CLA).

https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Contribution+Agreements
code_of_conduct_justification: ONAP adheres to the Linux Foundation Code of Conduct, found at https://lfprojects.org/policies/code-of-conduct/
roles_responsibilities_justification:
The key roles in the project and their responsibilities are described at

https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Community+Offices+and+Governance

Current members are listed at

https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=8226539
access_continuity_justification: For AAI we have multiple committers and multiple contributes who are listed in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Resources+and+Repositories#ResourcesandRepositories-ActiveandAvailableInventory All committers have access and rights to maintain the code base, approve and review incoming changes and release a new version of the artifact. This will let the project continue with minimal to no interruption if one person is incapacitated. Also this project is controlled by the linux foundation so we can add more committers if needed
bus_factor_justification: The project covered in this report have more than 2 persons who actively contribute and maintain code. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Resources+and+Repositories#ResourcesandRepositories-ActiveandAvailableInventory
documentation_roadmap_justification: Road map for AAI can be found in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/AAI+R3+Platform+Maturity?preview=%2F35523310%2F35523289%2FAAI+Roadmap+2018-01-05.pdf
documentation_architecture_justification: Architecture of AAI can be found in https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=1015836
documentation_quick_start_justification: Information on setting up ONAP can be found at https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/onap-developer/settingup/index.html
documentation_current_justification: Documentation is updated on a regular bases when needed.
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: No user interfaces; the project site is configurable for font size/colors.
internationalization_justification: It is not applicable at this point in time as the software will only be used by technical people and not by general public
maintenance_or_update_justification: All major releases are tagged in gerrit and the artifacts are stored with the release information on onap.nexus. So we can access all old versions of the artifact. If and when a upgrade requires certain steps to be followed they are being added to the release documents as needed
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: Vulnerabilities can be reported using the link https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=6591711 Currently we dont have any vulnerabilities reported, but the wiki page explains on how to report a vulnerability and how to report anonymously if you do not want the credit for it.
coding_standards_justification: Google coding style is used in ONAP https://github.com/google/styleguide
build_standard_variables_justification: The application does not create native binaries.
build_preserve_debug_justification: The application does not create native binaries.
build_non_recursive_justification: The application does not create native binaries.
build_repeatable_justification: All releases are tagged in gerrit(git), and the builds are controlled using jenkins. By providing the git tag information the same image can be build over and over again with same bit-for-bit result.
installation_standard_variables_justific: The compiled docker images and jar files can be installed/used as the user sees fit. Both run on JVM or docker.
installation_development_quick_justifica: All the components require only java and maven to begin with for a developer to quickly install and test it. Even for deployment using OOM and the right amount of resources, we can deploy the full AAI/ONAP suite in less than a day. The steps are documented in https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/oom.git/docs/oom_quickstart_guide.html
external_dependencies_justification: External dependencies are controlled using the pom file, which can be found in the root folder for the projects
dependency_monitoring_justification: We use sonatype CLM https://nexus-iq.wl.linuxfoundation.org/ and https://sonar.onap.org
updateable_reused_components_justificati: External components are maintained through Maven. The user can get a list of all included components using the maven dependency tree and can update or reuse as they see fit
interfaces_current_justification: We choose free open source solutions in every case and choose up-to-date versions of the components.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: https://jenkins.onap.org - on every commit, a verification job runs which runs an automated test suite. The code check in cannot pass with out jenkins posting a +1 on the review.
regression_tests_added50_justification: We add tests in these cases.
test_statement_coverage80_justification: AAI is working toward additional coverage but lack of resources prevent us from achieving it: https://sonar.onap.org
test_policy_mandated_justification: Contributing guide lines for development is recorded in https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
implement_secure_design_justification: AAI strives to implement secure design principles. We encrypt data where possible, and run security scans on the code and its dependencies.
input_validation_justification: The project strives to validate all input
crypto_credential_agility_justification: Credentials are separate and can be replaced without code compilation
